							Cactus Thieves Target Retiree Communities
						</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td style="font-size: 11pt;"> 
							
							<a href="#" OnClick="openpic('photos/CACTUS_RUSTLERS.jpg')"><IMG SRC="/DSDSMULTIMEDIA/photos/CACTUS_RUSTLERS.jpg" width="250" border="0" align="left"></a>
							Ed Sibiga stands behind one of many cacti in his front yard Friday, Jan. 24, 2003 in Surprise, Ariz. Sibiga is one of many who have had cactus stolen from their yards in recent months in a multi-thousand dollar theft ring. (AP Photo/Matt York)
							 
							<br>
							<br>
							02:45 AM EST January 29, 2003 
							<br>
							The Associated Press<br><br><br>SURPRISE, Ariz.<p class="nitfp">Retirees here have a prickly problem: cactus thieves.</p>
<p class="nitfp">Police say crooks have snatched cactuses from the yards of about 50 homes in Sun City and Sun City Grand, retirement communities west of Phoenix. Residents are on the lookout.</p>
<p class="nitfp">"Every morning I look out to see if my three cactus are still there," said Rose Marie Kery, 62. "We all have open yards, so we're just watching out for each other. The thieves clearly know we go to bed early."</p>
<p class="nitfp">The culprits - police suspect more than one person is involved - kick over five or six cactuses in each yard, said Surprise police Detective Scott Bailey. They target shallow-rooted golden barrel cactuses.</p>
<p class="nitfp">Bailey said the thieves may be posing as landscapers to swipe the yellow-spined cactuses, which retail at about $150 each. The losses have added up to about $10,000 in Sun City Grand alone, Bailey said.</p>
<p class="nitfp">Authorities said the thieves focus on newer houses. Homes here range from about $150,000 to $500,000 for houses nestled around private golf courses.</p>
<p class="nitfp">"Whether a cactus is important or not, we feel violated," said Bill Tenan, 60, whose house in Sun City Grand was hit two weeks ago.</p>
<p class="nitfp">Most residents don't report the theft to insurance companies because the deductibles are higher than the cost of replacing the plants.</p>
<p class="nitfp">Residents aren't the only ones hurt. Legitimate nurseries say they are forced to compete against what has become a cactus black market.</p>
<p class="nitfp">"Thieves are driving the price down and it costs us dearly," said Bob Johnson, owner of the Cactus King nursery.</p>

